{{Infobox ancient site |name = Hatula |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Israel |map_alt = |map_size = |location = |region = [[Israel]] |coordinates = {{coord|31.825556|34.9875|display=inline}} |type = semi-circular dwelling |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[PPNA]] |cultures = [[Natufian]], [[Khiamian]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 1981-1990 |archaeologists = Monique Lechevallier, Avraham Ronen |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = |public_access = |website = |notes = }} '''Hatula''' is an early [[Neolithic]] [[archeological]] site in the [[Judean hills]] south of [[Latrun]], beside Nahal Nachshon, in [[Israel]], {{convert|20|km|mi}} west of [[Jerusalem]].<ref>[http://cat.inist.fr/?aModele=afficheN&cpsidt=12076127 Ronen, A. Lechevallier, M., The Natufian and Early Neolithic site Hatula, near Latrun, Israel, Quartär, 35/36, pp. 141-164, 24, 1985.]</ref> The site is {{convert|15|m|ft}} above the riverbed on a rocky slope in an [[alluvial]] valley. Excavations revealed three levels of occupation in the [[Natufian]], [[Khiamian]] and [[PPNA]] (Sultanian).<ref name="Maisels2001">{{cite book|last=Maisels|first=Charles Keith|title=Early Civilizations of the Old World: The Formative Histories of Egypt, the Levant, Mesopotamia, India and China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7_hcCxJd9AC&pg=PA96|accessdate=8 July 2011|year=2001|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-10976-5|pages=96–}}</ref>
The site was excavated in eight seasons between 1981 and 1990 by Monique Lechevallier of the [[CNRS]] and Avraham Ronen from the [[University of Haifa]]. They unearthed a semi-circular dwelling with [[burial]] in the latest period. The site was suggested to have been a hunting station for flocks of [[gazelle]].<ref name="Maisels2001"/> [[Radiocarbon dating|Radiocarbon dates]] for the site suggest habitation between 10150 and 9320 BC by semi-sedentary groups.<ref name="Maisels2001"/> Evidence suggested domesticated [[dog]]s were present at the site.<ref name="Maisels2001"/><ref>{{cite book|title=The Natufian culture in the Levant|last1=Bar-Yosef|first1=Ofer|last2=Valla|first2=François Raymond|publisher=International Monographs in Prehistory|year=1991|isbn=1-879621-03-7|page=157}}</ref> Study of the [[Stone tool|lithic]] industry suggested the Khiamian was an adaptation of the Natufian in the area. Evidence of an accomplished [[bone industry]] were found but no signs of any grinding tools, art objects or building materials in the earliest two levels indicating a short term settlement pattern.<ref name="Maisels2001"/>
[[Archaeobotany|Archeaobotanical]] samples were taken from the Khiamian and Sultanian periods for [[phytolith]] analysis. This gave evidence of [[wheat]] at the site, along with an unidentified grass whose seeds were possibly a food source, both of which suggested that [[cereal]]s may have been part of the Natufian economy in Hatula. Changes in [[morphology (biology)|morphology]] of cells from husks of the [[grass]]es suggest a larger seed content, possibly due to increased exploitation, in the Sultanian.<ref name="PearsallPiperno1993">{{cite book|last1=Pearsall|first1=Deborah M.|last2=Piperno|first2=Dolores R.|title=Current Research in Phytolith Analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2N2DHjp1I_YC&pg=PA168|accessdate=8 July 2011|date=January 1993|publisher=UPenn Museum of Archaeology|isbn=978-1-931707-02-2|pages=168–}}</ref>
