'''Hüseyindede Tepe''' is an [[Early Hittite]] site in the [[Sungurlu]] district of Turkey's [[Çorum Province]], about 2&nbsp;km south of a town called '''Yörüklü''' (pop. 2,988 as of 2000). The site has been surveyed in 1997, leading to the discovery of the [[Hüseyindede vases]], one of which depicts dancers and processions and the other of which shows thirteen figures, with two in the act of [[bull-leaping|somersaulting over a bull]]. A third Hittite vase depicting dancers, musicians and acrobats was found in İnandık. The artwork is in Anatolian style and not an import from [[Minoan Crete]], the area mostly associated with [[bull-leaping]]. 

