'''Levi Savage Peterson''' (born 1933) is a [[Mormon]] biographer, essayist and fictionist whose best-known works include a seminal biography of [[Juanita Brooks]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/730412375|title=Juanita Brooks : the life story of a courageous historian of the Mountain Meadows Massacre|last=1933-|first=Peterson, Levi S.,|date=2011|publisher=University of Utah Press|others=Card, Royden,|isbn=9781607811510|location=Salt Lake City|oclc=730412375}}</ref> his own autobiography, and his novel ''[[The Backslider]]'', "standard for the contemporary Mormon novel".<ref>''People of Paradox'' by [[Terryl L. Givens]], page 313 (2007) {{ISBN|0-19-516711-2}}</ref> He was born and reared in the [[Mormon]] community of [[Snowflake, Arizona]] and is an emeritus professor of English at [[Weber State University]]. He edited ''[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]'' from 2004 to 2008.
Peterson's work as a writer centers in "the possibility of wrong behavior"; his works "variously examine the tension between Sainthood as fact and Sainthood as aspiration, between belief and doubt, and between expected blessings and the traumas of reality."<ref>{{cite web | title=1983 AML Award: Editing & Publishing Honorable Mention | publisher=[[Association for Mormon Letters]] | url=http://www.aml-online.org/Awards/Award.aspx?Id=1400 | accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref> Similarly, he taught his writing students to "Write from the other side of your inhibitions".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Karamesines|first1=Patricia|title=The Bright Side of the Dark Side|url=http://www.motleyvision.org/2007/the-bright-side-of-the-dark-side/|website=A Motley Vision|accessdate=12 September 2017|date=16 February 2007}}</ref>
